 Jackson offers new and unorthodox accounts of the coming-to-fame of some of Britain’s most revered authors and compares their reputations and afterlives with those of their contemporary rivals. What she discovers about trends, champions, institutional power, and writers’ conscious efforts to position themselves for posterity casts fresh light on the actual processes that lead to literary fame.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAuthors and readerszEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aAuthors, EnglishxAppreciationy19th century. 0aAuthorshipxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismy19th century. 0aFamexHistoryy19th century. 0aInfluence (Literary, artistic, etc.)xHistoryy19th century. 0aReputationzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aRomanticismzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030017479340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021330040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213300423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300213300/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY